Linear Search (Sequential search)¶

From left to right, scan every element in the line values until find the target in the line.

  • The worst case complexity is O(n), sometimes known an O(n) search.
  • Search time increases with the number of elements.

# If found, return the index of target
values = [ 9, 5, 8, 7, 7, 3, 1, 2 ]
target = 7
N = len(values)

i = 0
while i < N:
  if target == values[i]: #found
    break
  i += 1 #move to next

f"Found at {i}" if i < N else f"Not Found"
Out[ ]:
'Found at 3'

Binary Search¶

Divide-and-conquer

The premise of binary search is the values have already been sorted.

Each time we cut the search space into halves, low half and high half. and reduce the search space (region) to one half.

The run time complexity is O($log_{2}{N}$).

In [10]:
%%html
<iframe src="https://liveexample.pearsoncmg.com/dsanimation13ejava/BinarySearcheBook.html" width="800" height="400"></iframe>

Flow chart¶

  • Sort the values in ascending order

  • With the sorted values V, do:

  • IF target < Low or target > High: exit

  • ELSE:

  1. Set Low = 0, High = N-1
  2. Repeat:
  3. set mid = High // 2
  4. IF target == V[Low] or target == V[High]: found and exit
  5. While mid != Low and mid != High, do:
    • compare target and V[mid]
      • target == V[mid]: found!
      • target < V[mid] : set High = mid-1
      • target > V[mid] : set Low = mid+1
In [7]:
V = [ 9, 5, 8, 7, 7, 3, 1, 2 ]
V.sort() # [ 1, 2, 3, 5, 7, 7, 8, 9 ]
key = 4
N = len(V)

if key < V[0] or key > V[-1]: 
  print("Not Found")
else:
  Low, High = 0, N-1
  print(f"Low, High = {Low}, {High}") 
  while High >= Low:
    mid = (Low + High) // 2
    if key == V[mid]:
      print(f"Found at {mid}")
      break
    elif key < V[mid]:
      High = mid - 1
      print(f"Low, High = {Low}, {High}")
    else:
      Low = mid + 1
      print(f"Low, High = {Low}, {High}")

Low, High = 0, 7
Low, High = 0, 2
Low, High = 2, 2
Low, High = 3, 2

Exercises¶

Write a Python function binarySearch(V, key) which takes a sorted List object L and a search key, and returns the index of key in V if the key is found and -1 if the key is not found.

Write a test program that prompts the user to enter a group of values and a search key, displays the index of key in the values if the key is found or "-1" if not found.
